Original fission chamber efficiency given
Uncertainty and covariances for (n,n') scattering.
150 MeV Geel electron Linac, GELINA.
The differential gamma production cross-sections at
110 and respectively 150 deg were derived
normalising point by point the HPGe yield to the
235U fission chamber yield and to the 235U(n,f)
cross-section.
At high neutron energy for the main transitions and on
full energy range for the less probable transitions
few channels of 8 ns time-of-flight were grouped
together to keep the relative stat. unc. in
acceptable limits.
The following corrections were done:
- Multiplication of original data (BgNS Transactions
Rev.C91(2015)064618) to correct for fission chamber
efficiency redetermination;
- for distance between positions of 207Pb sample and
the position of the fission chamber.
- for gamma-ray detection efficiency: extended volume
source and self-attenuation of gamma rays in the
207Pb sample corrected by means of MCNP4c2
simulations. The HPGe efficiencies were corrected
for coincident gamma rays from the 152Eu source.
This correction was about 1%. Summing peaks of
gamma rays with X-rays were not observed as the
latter are absorbed by detector cap and dead layer.
- Angular distribution: Gauss quadrature. The integral
gamma production cross-section was calculated as a
weighted sum of the differential gamma production
cross-section at 150 and 110 degrees (roots of the
4th order Legendre polynomial). The contribution
of the opening angle of the HPGe detectors is
negligible for this integration method.
- Multiple scattering and attenuation of the neutron
beam in the 207Pb sample. This was done with MCNP
(version 4c2) simulations. The multiple scattering
and neutron attenuation coefficient used in the
calculations is given point by point with the
integral gamma production cross-section. No
multiple scattering and neutron attenuation
correction was applied for the (n,2n)
cross-sections. Only neutron attenuation will be
significant for the (n,2n) cross-sections and this
is estimated to be less than 2%.
- No acquisition dead time was observed. To avoid the
possible dead time introduced in the HPGe detectors
acquisition system by the pile-up between the
neutron induced events and the gamma-flash induced
events all the neutron bursts in which a
gamma-flash was detected were rejected. An inhibit
signal was created independently for each HPGe
detector to block the acquisition system if a
gamma-flash induced event was detected. These
signals set flags in the fission chamber
acquisition systems and the same bursts were
rejected. The rejected bursts represented 9.7% for
the detector at 110 deg and 17.7% at 150 deg.
The analytical expressions employed are detailed in
the above mentioned NIM paper.
Together with the list of uncertainties on the
quantities in these expressions listed above this
will allow the evaluator to construct the covariance
matrix.
In this we comply with the method recommended by
F.Froehner JEFF report 18, OECD-NEA Paris (2000) and
D.L. Smith, Neutron Physics and Nuclear Data in
Science and Technology, Vol.4, OECD-NEA, Paris ISBN
2 large volume HPGe detectors, with
closed-ended coaxial geometry.
The relative efficiency was 75.9% for the detector at
110 deg and 104% for the detector at 150 deg.
The gamma-energy resolution was 2.4 keV at 1.332 MeV.
The time resolution of the HPGe detectors was about
5 ns.
The distance to the centre of the 207Pb sample was
139 mm (110 deg) and 146 mm (150 deg).
Total uncertainties for the cross sections
(1 sigma) were deduced by combining partial
uncertainties from various sources in quadrature.
Uncertainty sources considered were:
- HPGe efficiencies uncertainties around 2% for both
detectors except below 500keV where, because of the
large attenuation and of the Slow Rise Time
Rejection, the absolute efficiency uncertainties
increase up to 6% at 300keV. This uncertainties
includes the statistical counting uncertainties,
calibration source activity error and MCNP
simulations error;
- 235U(n,f)cross-section uncertainties are point
dependent and are given above together the 235U(n,f)
cross-sections values;
- Statistical counting uncertainties for HPGe
detectors and fission chamber are point dependent.
The statistical counting uncertainties of the
fission chamber yield range from about 1.4% at
2 MeV up to about 3% at 18 MeV;
Fission chamber efficiency uncertainty (1.62%).
150 MeV Geel electron Linac, GELINA.
Rotary uranium target that is struck by an
electron beam with a mean energy of 105 MeV and an
average current of 70 uA.
Time-of-flight technique with a 198.551 m flight
path and neutron bursts of 1 ns at a rate of 800 Hz.
The resolution was 8 ns time-of-flight which
corresponds to 1.12 keV at 1 MeV and 35.7 keV at
10 MeV.
The two HPGe detectors and the fission chamber
recorded simultaneously.
The time resolution of the time coder was 0.5 ns.
Conventional electronics for both HPGe detectors and
fission chamber and the constant fraction.
Discriminators of the HPGe detectors were set up on
slow rise time rejection function.
The neutron beam was collimated before the fission
chamber and its diameter was of 6.1 cm, less than the
diameter of the 235U deposits and than the diameter
of 207Pb sample.
The HPGe efficiencies were measured with a standard
point source of 152Eu of 3.1E+4 Bq, in the sample
position.

The neutron flux was measured with a multilayer 235U
fission chamber, vacuum evaporated deposits, with a
total areal density of 3.066(6) 235U mg/cm2.
The chamber had 5 layers, 3 two-sided and 2 one-sided.
Isotopic composition of the U deposits was 99.826(8)%
The fission chamber was placed at 197.214 m flight
path.
